{{Expand English|date=August 2024}}
[[File:20040906yunankama.jpg|230px|thumb|Traditional kiln work in {{ill|Yunnan Province|ja|雲南省|12=draft}}, China. Producing {{ill|clay tiles|ja|粘土瓦|12=draft}} by splitting cylindrical ceramic forms fired in kilns.]]

'''Kilnwork''' (窯業, ''yōgyō'') refers to the industrial process of using high-temperature treatment of {{ill|clay|ja|粘土|12=draft}}, {{ill|quartz sand|ja|ケイ砂|12=draft}}, {{ill|limestone|ja|石灰岩|12=draft}}, and other {{ill|non-metallic materials|ja|非金属|12=draft}} to produce {{ill|ceramics|ja|陶磁器|12=draft}}, {{ill|tiles|ja|瓦|12=draft}}, {{ill|glass|ja|ガラス|12=draft}}, {{ill|cement|ja|セメント|12=draft}}, and other {{ill|ceramics|ja|セラミックス|12=draft}} (also referred to as ceramic products or kilnwork products)<ref>[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%AA%AF%E6%A5%AD-145615 "Sekai Daijiten 2nd Edition, Daijirin 3rd Edition"]</ref>. The term originates from the use of {{ill|kilns|ja|窯|12=draft}}. Traditional fuels for kilns included {{ill|firewood|ja|薪|12=draft}}, {{ill|charcoal|ja|炭|12=draft}}, and {{ill|coal|ja|石炭|12=draft}}, but modern kilns often use {{ill|oil-fired boilers|ja|石油|12=draft}} or {{ill|electric kilns|ja|電気窯|12=draft}}.

In ancient times, most houses had {{ill|thatch|ja|草葺|12=draft}} or {{ill|straw roofs|ja|茅葺|12=draft}}, but from the medieval period, {{ill|clay tiles|ja|粘土瓦|12=draft}} began to be used for roofing, especially in houses of aristocrats, samurai, and monks. The ability to produce {{ill|porcelain|ja|磁器|12=draft}} and {{ill|crystal glass|ja|クリスタルガラス|12=draft}} elevated these items as valued furnishings, even gaining recognition as art objects. The professions of {{ill|potters|ja|陶工|12=draft}} and {{ill|ceramic artists|ja|陶芸家|12=draft}} thus established themselves with considerable social status. Similarly, {{ill|cloisonné|ja|七宝|12=draft}} and {{ill|glass art|ja|ガラス|12=draft}} were appreciated as decorative crafts. However, in many {{ill|developing countries|ja|開発途上国|12=draft}} with small-scale traditional kilnwork, a significant volume of production remains devoted to building materials like {{ill|tiles|ja|瓦|12=draft}}, alongside ceramics and tableware.

In recent years, {{ill|siding materials|ja|窯業系サイディング材|12=draft}} categorized under kilnwork have become increasingly popular in construction. Their short construction time, excellent design properties, and ability to address labor shortages of {{ill|carpenters|ja|大工|12=draft}} and {{ill|plasterers|ja|左官|12=draft}} have driven the market demand, capturing approximately 70% of the external wall share in detached housing.

== Education ==

* '''Kilnwork High Schools''': As of April 2021, the {{ill|Aichi Prefectural Seto Kilnwork High School|ja|愛知県立瀬戸窯業高等学校|12=draft}} was renamed {{ill|Aichi Prefectural Seto Technical High School|ja|愛知県立瀬戸工科高等学校|12=draft}}, making "kilnwork" as part of school names extinct.
* '''Specialized Kilnwork Schools''': The {{ill|Saga Prefectural Arita Kilnwork College|ja|佐賀県立有田窯業大学校|12=draft}} remains the sole institution of its kind.

