[[File:20040906yunankama.jpg|230px|thumb|Traditional kiln work in [[:en:Yunnan|Yunnan Province]], China. Producing {{ill|clay tiles|ja|粘土瓦|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/clay tiles|qq=}} by splitting cylindrical ceramic forms fired in kilns.]]

'''Kilnwork''' (窯業, ''yōgyō'') refers to the industrial process of using high-temperature treatment of [[:en:Clay|clay]], {{ill|quartz sand|ja|ケイ砂|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/quartz sand|qq=}}, [[:en:Limestone|limestone]], and other {{ill|non-metallic materials|ja|非金属|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/non-metallic materials|qq=}} to produce [[:en:Pottery|ceramics]], [[:en:Roof tiles|tiles]], [[:en:Glass|glass]], [[:en:Cement|cement]], and other [[:en:Ceramic|ceramics]] (also referred to as ceramic products or kilnwork products)<ref>[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%AA%AF%E6%A5%AD-145615 "Sekai Daijiten 2nd Edition, Daijirin 3rd Edition"]</ref>. The term originates from the use of [[:en:Kiln|kilns]]. Traditional fuels for kilns included [[:en:Firewood|firewood]], [[:en:Char (chemistry)|charcoal]], and [[:en:Coal|coal]], but modern kilns often use [[:en:Petroleum|oil-fired boilers]] or {{ill|electric kilns|ja|電気窯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/electric kilns|qq=}}.

In ancient times, most houses had {{ill|thatch|ja|草葺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/thatch|qq=}} or [[:en:Thatching|straw roofs]], but from the medieval period, {{ill|clay tiles|ja|粘土瓦|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/clay tiles|qq=}} began to be used for roofing, especially in houses of aristocrats, samurai, and monks. The ability to produce [[:en:Porcelain|porcelain]] and {{ill|crystal glass|ja|クリスタルガラス|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/crystal glass|qq=}} elevated these items as valued furnishings, even gaining recognition as art objects. The professions of {{ill|potters|ja|陶工|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/potters|qq=}} and {{ill|ceramic artists|ja|陶芸家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ceramic artists|qq=}} thus established themselves with considerable social status. Similarly, [[:en:Cloisonné|cloisonné]] and [[:en:Glass|glass art]] were appreciated as decorative crafts. However, in many [[:en:Developing country|developing countries]] with small-scale traditional kilnwork, a significant volume of production remains devoted to building materials like [[:en:Roof tiles|tiles]], alongside ceramics and tableware.

In recent years, {{ill|siding materials|ja|窯業系サイディング材|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/siding materials|qq=}} categorized under kilnwork have become increasingly popular in construction. Their short construction time, excellent design properties, and ability to address labor shortages of [[:en:Carpentry|carpenters]] and [[:en:Plasterwork|plasterers]] have driven the market demand, capturing approximately 70% of the external wall share in detached housing.

== Education ==

* '''Kilnwork High Schools''': As of April 2021, the {{ill|Aichi Prefectural Seto Kilnwork High School|ja|愛知県立瀬戸窯業高等学校|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aichi Prefectural Seto Kilnwork High School|qq=}} was renamed {{ill|Aichi Prefectural Seto Technical High School|ja|愛知県立瀬戸工科高等学校|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aichi Prefectural Seto Technical High School|qq=}}, making "kilnwork" as part of school names extinct.
* '''Specialized Kilnwork Schools''': The {{ill|Saga Prefectural Arita Kilnwork College|ja|佐賀県立有田窯業大学校|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saga Prefectural Arita Kilnwork College|qq=}} remains the sole institution of its kind.

